NHS prescribes controversial HIV drug to 10,000 patients
Patients will receive access to 'transformative' treatment to HIV prevention from September on the basis of a Supreme Court's decision to fund the NHS drug.
The English National Health Service (NSH) reported that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is used before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered via the health service to approximately 10,000 patients in the three-year trial period.
The NSH agreed to finance the probationary period after the appeals court supported the Supreme Court's decision last year to say that the NHS had the funds to pay for PrEP despite the statement that the medicine should be funded by the local authorities.
The decision, announced on Thursday, was taken by the NHS of England from the mouths of Director-General Simon Stevens as a 'significant intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a 'decisive moment'.
The Sexual Health Clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start admitting patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018 there will be a full implementation across England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV.
Tests showed that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission between patients at risk.
The pre-sex exercise PrEP means that there are a sufficient number of specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent the infection.
These medicines can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include homosexual or bisexual men, transgender people and people with HIV-positive partners who are unsuccessful.
Clinics will designate eligible participants who sign up to agree to participate in the testing, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with the GP in the UK can also sign up at their local sexual health clinic to apply for potential participation in the testing.
The program will cost the taxpayer £10 million, and the NHS of England signed a contract this week to distribute the drugs following the acquisition of an international public contract.
The test period is proposed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: 'This important intervention should be replenished and fully occupied by the ever-expanding and increasingly successful attempt to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in a more than 30-year effort to halt one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, Executive Director of NAT (National Aids Trust) said: 'We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and at risk to patients, it will offer the possibility of transforming the English HIV epidemic.
The NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection with a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to coax the partner from September, leading to improvements in the quality of many lives.
We accept this statement with pleasure.'
Ian Green, managing director of Terrence Higgins Trust said: 'The number one priority must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure that it is made available to each patient.
We now have a PrEP test drug at our disposal and are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of being infected with HIV.'
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: 'The start of the pre-court trial period of the PrEP is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and endangering the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
The subsequent tests will take us one step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start the tests as soon as possible throughout the country, protecting those who are exposed to HIV and together to put an end to the spread of HIV in society.'
