Get to know the plant with one click.
Students with herbarian creation and ordinary plant lovers will be helped by the new free application Pl@ntNet.
When they're interested in what plant they've just come across on a walk, this app will advise them.
All they'll have to do is photograph the plant, and the app itself recognizes what kind it is.
The new app, which is available for both iOS and Android, was presented on Tuesday by representatives of the CEEV Ethics and Environmental Education Centre in Bratislava's Mountain Park as part of the Secret Life of the City project.
The project also involved pupils from 50 Czech and Slovak schools, who photographed and added plants from their surroundings with the app's app's database.
The newly created French app is free to download on the Secret Life of the City website.
The main goal of the French programmers was for as many people as possible to contribute to the app with their images, thus increasing the number of plants that the application can recognize.
"Already children who can hold a tablet or mobile phone in their hand can go to the forest," said this project's coordinator, Ivana Poláčková.
Based on a high-quality photo of the flower, leaf or fetus of the plant, the application can recognize its name in seconds, which in both Czech and Slovak is added under the photo.
The French allowed us to translate the application into Slovak and Czech into the Secret Life of the City project.
It is therefore welcome that users should contribute to the app with a picture of the plant that is not yet found in the database after opening an account.
"The French will evaluate whether it is beneficial and then add it to the database," Poláčková informed.
GMB's concerns about investing in the McVitie's factory in Glasgow
The union is demanding assurances from the crack makers McVitie's about the long-running commitment to be produced at the Glasgow factory.
The Scottish GMB union said the company was silent for the time being about any investment in the Tollcross factory.
The factory employs more than 500 employees who produce, among other products, the Hobnob and Rich Tea biscuits.
The owner of McVitie's, Pladis, said it had invested more than £5 million in the area in the entire area over the previous few years.
It added that the employees and representatives of the trade unions would be "between the first informed" in the event of changes to the operation of the factory.
In a letter to the building company, the GMB, Scotland's GMB unions expressed their fears that McVitie's would "not get its promises to finance and upgrade the production lines."
GMB's main organizer Drew Duffy added: "The fact that we have not received a clear response from the site supervisor about the needs of the company and the future investment plan in Tollcross is very worrying for our members.
Generations of many families have worked here, and employees come mostly from the local community and the Glasgow area, where working at the local factory is a critical pillar of decent employment in the area of high unemployment and social separation.
From a point of view of work, salaries, and utility - and despite the outlook for Brexit, rising cost of living, and falling slow production - the eastern part of Glasgow needs a desperately prosperous producer like McVitie's."
A spokesperson for Pladis said: "The Tollcross manager received a letter from GMB only yesterday and the company will issue a statement as soon as possible, as we appreciate the continuing commitment to the employees and representatives of the unions.
A regular meeting with the staff and GMB representatives in Tollcross took place two months ago and many of the problems were openly discussed at this meeting.
We were talking to employees that, as in all companies operating in extremely competitive and insecure economic conditions, we assess our operations on a regular basis, which is true for all our operations, so that we can continue to successfully compete with others.
To this she added: "In recent years, we have invested £5 million in the Tollcross area, mainly in production lines and streamlining of operations.
We greatly appreciate the heritage of Tollcross and the site and, in the event of any changes in the operation of the factory, the employees and representatives of the trade unions will be informed immediately."
